article.headline: Oregon State 71, Jackson State 59
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Oregon State freshman guard Angelo Tsagarakis missed all five of his 3-point attempts in the first half against Jackson State. "That was too many," he said. Tsagarakis went on to score 14 points, including three 3-pointers, as the Beavers overcame a slow start and defeated the injury-hampered Tigers 71-59 Sunday. David Lucas had 11 points and 10 rebounds for the Beavers (6-4), who have won four of their last six games. Tsagarakis, who has become known for his shooting, finished 3-for-10 from 3-point range but was a perfect 5-for-5 from the free throw line. Jackson State, making the final stop on an eight-game road trip, was without starters Michael Travis and Leonard Taylor, who both had ankle injuries from the Tigers' 69-56 loss to South Alabama on Tuesday. Ishmael Joyce finished with 14 points for Jackson State (2-7). After taking a narrow 28-26 lead in a back-and-forth first half, the Beavers jumped ahead 35-29 on Lamar Hurd's slam early in the second. Oregon State, coming off a 76-73 victory over Sacramento State last Monday, went up 44-34 on J.S. Nash's layup, and went on to lead by as many as 24 points. Jackson State jumped out 8-2 early in the game, but the Beavers quickly made up the difference, and took an 11-10 lead on Jim Hanchett's dunk. But the Tigers were tenacious, and hung in despite their injury problems. "They're disciplined to the point that they're going to do what they do," Oregon State coach Jay John said about the Tigers. "They're going to keep playing." The Beavers appeared to take control when Vic Remmers' 3-pointer put them up 16-14, but Jackson State kept up and took a 21-19 lead on K.C. Cavette's layup. The two teams were tied at 26 with 35.8 seconds left, but Nash's pair of free throws gave the Beavers the halftime edge. "The first half wasn't very pretty," John said. The game was the last tune up for both teams as they ready for their conference schedules. Oregon State visits Pac-10 foe UCLA on Friday night, while Jackson State hosts Southwestern Athletic Conference opponent Alabama A&M on Saturday. Nash was confident for the Beavers' Pac-10 season. "If we get hot and we're on a roll, we can be as good as anybody in the conference," he said. ^
